# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aluminium-monofluoride
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Alternatively acetamide can be obtained in excellent yield via ammonolysis of acetylacetone under conditions commonly used in reductive amination.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] It can also be made from anhydrous acetic acid, acetonitrile and very well dried hydrogen chloride gas, using an ice bath, alongside more valuable reagent acetyl chloride.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Yield is typically low (up to 35%), and the acetamide made this way is generated as a salt with HCl.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Acetamide is used as a plasticizer and an industrial solvent.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Molten acetamide is good solvent with a broad range of applicability.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Notably, its dielectric constant is higher than most organic solvents, allowing it to dissolve inorganic compounds with solubilities closely analogous to that of water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Acetamide has uses in electrochemistry and the organic synthesis of pharmaceuticals, pesticides, and antioxidants for plastics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] Acetamide has been detected near the center of the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] This finding is potentially significant because acetamide has an amide bond, similar to the essential bond between amino acids in proteins.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] This finding lends support to the theory that organic molecules that can lead to life (as we know it on Earth) can form in space.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetamide] In addition, acetamide is found infrequently on burning coal dumps, as a mineral of the same name.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile was first prepared in 1847 by the French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is used mainly as a solvent in the purification of butadiene in refineries.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Specifically, acetonitrile is fed into the top of a distillation column filled with hydrocarbons including butadiene, and as the acetonitrile falls down through the column, it absorbs the butadiene which is then sent from the bottom of the tower to a second separating tower.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Heat is then employed in the separating tower to separate the butadiene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] In the laboratory, it is used as a medium-polarity non-protic solvent that is miscible with water and a range of organic solvents, but not saturated hydrocarbons.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It has a convenient range of temperatures at which it is a liquid, and dissolves a wide range of ionic and nonpolar compounds and is useful as a mobile phase in HPLC and LC–MS.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It is widely used in battery applications because of its relatively high dielectric constant and ability to dissolve electrolytes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] For similar reasons, it is a popular solvent in cyclic voltammetry.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Its ultraviolet transparency UV cutoff, low viscosity and low chemical reactivity make it a popular choice for high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile plays a significant role as the dominant solvent used in oligonucleotide synthesis from nucleoside phosphoramidites.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Industrially, it is used as a solvent for the manufacture of pharmaceuticals and photographic film.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is a common two-carbon building block in organic synthesis of many useful chemicals, including acetamidine hydrochloride, thiamine, and 1-naphthaleneacetic acid, along with more complex nitriles.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Its reaction with cyanogen chloride affords malononitrile.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile has a free electron pair at the nitrogen atom, which can form many transition metal nitrile complexes.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] A related complex is tetrakis(acetonitrile)copper(I) hexafluorophosphate [Cu(CH3CN)4]+.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The CH3CN ligands in these complexes are rapidly displaced.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It also forms Lewis adducts with group 13 Lewis acids like boron trifluoride.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] In superacids, it is possible to protonate acetonitrile.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile is a byproduct from the manufacture of acrylonitrile by catalytic ammoxidation of propylene.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Most is combusted to support the intended process but an estimated several thousand tons are retained for the above-mentioned applications.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Production trends for acetonitrile thus generally follow those of acrylonitrile.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] In 1992, 14,700 tonnes (16,200 short tons) of acetonitrile were produced in the US.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetonitrile has only modest toxicity in small doses.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It can be metabolised to produce hydrogen cyanide, which is the source of the observed toxic effects.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Generally the onset of toxic effects is delayed, due to the time required for the body to metabolize acetonitrile to cyanide (generally about 2–12 hours).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Cases of acetonitrile poisoning in humans are rare but not unknown by inhalation and ingestion.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The symptoms, which do not usually appear for several hours after the exposure, include breathing difficulties, slow pulse rate, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Convulsions and coma can occur in serious cases, followed by death from respiratory failure.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The treatment is as for cyanide poisoning, with oxygen, sodium nitrite, and sodium thiosulfate among the most commonly used emergency treatments.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It has been used in a formulation for removal of sculptured fingernails.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] At least two cases have been reported of accidental poisoning of young children by acetonitrile-based sculptured nail remover, one of which was fatal.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Acetone and ethyl acetate are often preferred as safer for domestic use, and acetonitrile has been banned in cosmetic products in the European Economic Area since March 2000.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] In common with other nitriles, acetonitrile can be metabolised in microsomes, especially in the liver, to produce hydrogen cyanide, as was first shown by Pozzani *et al.* in 1959.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The first step in this pathway is the oxidation of acetonitrile to glycolonitrile by an NADPH-dependent cytochrome P450 monooxygenase.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The glycolonitrile then undergoes a spontaneous decomposition to give hydrogen cyanide and formaldehyde.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Formaldehyde, a toxin and a carcinogen on its own, is further oxidized to formic acid, which is another source of toxicity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The metabolism of acetonitrile is much slower than that of other nitriles, which accounts for its relatively low toxicity.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] Hence, one hour after administration of a potentially lethal dose, the concentration of cyanide in the rat brain was ⁠1/20⁠ that for a propionitrile dose 60 times lower (see table).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The relatively slow metabolism of acetonitrile to hydrogen cyanide allows more of the cyanide produced to be detoxified within the body to thiocyanate (the rhodanese pathway).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] It also allows more acetonitrile to be excreted unchanged before it is metabolised.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/acetonitrile] The main pathways of excretion are by exhalation and in the urine.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/aluminium-monofluoride] This molecule has been detected in the interstellar medium, where molecules are so dilute that intermolecular collisions are unimportant.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Despite the above synthetic scheme successfully producing tetrameters of [Cp*Al]4 at reasonable yields (44%), its use of AlCl proved problematic, as AlCl synthesis requires harsh conditions and its reactive nature makes storage a challenge.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] More exotic ways of synthesizing [Cp*Al]4 include the controlled disproportionation of an Al(II) dialane into constituent Al(I) and Al(III) products.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] For example, reacting dialane [Cp*AlBr]2 with a Lewis base such as pyridine the Lewis base stabilized [Cp*AlBr2] and [Cp*Al]4.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Monomeric Cp*Al has also been isolated in a solid Ar matrix by heating [Cp*Al]4 in toluene to 133 °C and spraying the resultant vapours with Ar onto a copper block kept at 12 K.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] X-ray crystallographic data determined Cp*Al to exist exclusively as a tetramer in its solid state.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] This tetramer, [Cp*Al]4, consists of an Al4 tetrahedron, and the Cp* rings are η5-coordinated to the aluminium(I) cation such that the planes of the C5Me5- rings are approximately parallel to the opposite base of the Al4 tetrahedron.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] The perpendicular distance between Al and the Cp* ring was determined through crystallography to range from 199.7 to 203.2 pm, with a mean value of 201.5 pm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] The Al-Al bond in [Cp*Al]4 is 276.9 pm, which is slightly shorter than that of metallic aluminium, which has an Al-Al bond length of 286 pm.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Additional characterization that has been performed include Raman spectroscopy, which detected a Raman active breathing vibration (A1, 377 cm-1) of the Al4 tetrahedron in [Cp*Al]4.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Natural bond orbital (NBO) analysis of [Cp*Al] and [Cp*Al]4 using B3LYP/6-31G(d,p) calculated the average charge transfer per Cp* fragment to an Al atom to be 0.657 and 0.641 respectively.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] This is slightly higher than the charge transfers calculated on [CpAl] and [Cp*Al]4 (0.630 and 0.591 respectively).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Atoms in molecules (AIM) calculations calculate the Al-Al bonding to be metallic.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Stabilization of [Cp*Al]4 relative to [CpAl]4 is thought to arise from addition of H-H interactions on the methyl groups attached to the Cp* ligand as opposed to the increased Al-Al bonding interactions.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Despite its typically tetrameric form, the monomer Cp*Al has been isolated and studied in the gas-phase using gas-phase electron diffraction.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] In its gaseous monomeric form, the perpendicular distance between the Al to the Cp* ring was calculated to be 206.3(8) pm, which is slightly longer than tetrameric [Cp*Al]4.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] At temperatures above 100 °C, [Cp*Al]4 decomposes to form pentamethylcyclopentandiene (Cp*H), metallic aluminium (Al(0)) and other non-volatile Al(III) compounds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] The overall stability of [Cp*Al]4 is unique as there is a thermodynamic affinity for tetrameric aluminium(I) compounds ([RAl]4) to disproportionate into elemental aluminium and R3Al.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] As such, a number of different novel oligomeric structures can be synthesised when using tetrameric [Cp*Al]4 as a precursor.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] For example, treatment of [Cp*Al]4 with excess selenium and tellurium in mild conditions gives the unique heterocubane structures [Cp*AlSe]4 and [Cp*AlTe]4 respectively.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] These heterocubane structures are extremely air and moisture sensitive, leading to its decomposition and evolution of H2Se and H2Te respectively.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Analogously, reaction of [Cp*Al]4 with lighter chalcogens such as O2, N2O and sulfur yield [Cp*AlX]4 (X = O, S).
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] [Cp*Al]4 was also the used as a precursor to synthesize the first ever stable dimeric iminoalane containing an Al2N2 heterocycle through the treatment of [Cp*Al]4 with Me3SiN3 in a 1:4 molar ratio.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] The resultant iminoalanes was characterized to contain an ideally planar Al2N2 core ring with three coordinate aluminium and nitrogen atoms.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Other dimeric iminoalanes including [Cp*AlNSi(*i*-Pr)3]2, [Cp*AlNSiPh3]2 and [Cp*AlNSi(*t*-Bu)3]2 have since been synthesized using [Cp*Al]4 as a precursor through oxidative addition of an organic azide.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] [Cp*Al] is able to act as an atypical exotic ligand in donor-acceptor type bonds.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] For example, mixing [Cp*Al]4 with the Lewis acidic B(C6F6)3 forms the Al-B donor-acceptor type bond, and results in the synthesis of the adduct [Cp*Al-B(C6F6)3].
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Analogous main-group complexes that have been synthesised and characterised include dialane complexes [Cp*Al-Al(C6F5)3] and [Cp*Al-Al(*t*-Bu)3], and group 13-group 13 complexes [Cp*Al-Ga(*t*-Bu)3].
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] [Cp*Al] is also able to act as a potent ligand to transition metals.
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] For example, treatment of [Cp*Al] with [(dcpe)Pt(H)(CH2*t*-Bu)] (dcpe = bis(dicyclohexylphosphino)ethane) yields [(dcpe)Pt(Cp*Al)2].
[src:aluminium-monofluoride/pentamethylcyclopentadienyl-aluminium-i] Other transition metals which use [Cp*Al] as a ligand include, but are not limited to d10 metal centre complexes such as [Pd(Cp*Al)4] and [Ni(Cp*Al)4], and lanthanide/actinide metal centre complexes such as (CpSiMe3)3U-AlCp*, (CpSiMe3)3Nd-AlCp* and (CpSiMe3)3Ce-AlCp*.
